questionContent.body: If second and fourth Saturdays and all the Sundays are taken as only holidays for an office, what would be the minimum number of possible working days of any month of any year?

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
February has the minimum number of days: 28 (in a non-leap year)

There are exactly 4 Sundays in 28 days ⇒ 4 Sunday holidays

There are 4 Saturdays; 2nd and 4th are holidays ⇒ 2 Saturday holidays

Total holidays = 4 (Sundays) + 2 (Saturdays) = 6

Working days = 28 - 6 = 22

✅ Minimum possible working days in any month = 22

questionContent.body: January 1, 2007 was Monday. What day of the week lies on Jan. 1, 2008?

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Answer:B

  1. From Jan 1, 2007 (Monday) to Jan 1, 2008, 2007 is not leap → 1 odd day.
  2. Monday + 1 = Tuesday.

questionContent.body: January 1, 2008 is Tuesday. What day of the week lies on Jan 1, 2009?

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Answer:C

2008 is a leap year, so it has 2 odd days. Adding 2 days to Tuesday (Jan 1, 2008) gives Thursday.

Therefore, Jan 1, 2009 was a Thursday.

Study the following information carefully and answer the questions given beside. 


Certain number of persons are sitting around a circular table and facing towards the center of the table. Some of them own different cars.

No two persons have same car.   Three persons are sitting between Thakur and the one, who owns Renault.

Two persons are sitting between Thakur and Prince. Robert is sitting second to the left of Prince. Samuel is sitting second to the left of Robert.

Samuel and Thakur are not the immediate neighbors. Qasim is sitting second to the right of Thakur.

The one, who owns Ford, is sitting third to the left of Qasim. The one, who owns Hyundai, is sitting second to the left of the one, who owns Ford.

Three persons are not sitting between the one, who owns Renault and the one, who owns Honda, when counted from the right of the one, who owns Honda. The one, who sits immediate left of Samuel, owns Honda. Number of persons sitting between Qasim and Prince, when counted from right of Prince is four times as the number of persons sitting between Samuel and Qasim, when counted from left of Samuel.
Which of the following statements prove that ‘W > F’ is definitely true?

questionOptions.body: A ≥ J < K = W ≥ L > Z; J > N = S ≤ F
W < P < Q ≤ K > J > Z; Z = H ≥ S = A < F
S < J < W = O ≤ L < Q; S = P ≤ K < F =J
None of the above

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Solution: III


Option A: J > S ≤ F → J > F not definite → W > F not definite

Option B: W < P... and A < F, but no link between W and F → not definite

Option C: S < J < W and F = J ⇒ W > F ✅

W > J, J = F → so W > F is definitely true

Only Option C gives a definite conclusion

✅ Correct answer: C
